Team 23 Final Project: Citi Bike in NYC¶

Jiaxuan Alice Ji and Fuman Annie Xie¶

Introduction¶

Project Description¶

Our project aims to gain insights into the New York City Citi Bikesharing service, focusing on three key aspects: user demand, user type, and bike type. With the rising popularity of shared bikes as a means of commuting, particularly in the post-Covid era, our project is interested in investigating user demand, taking into account weather conditions and user profiles. Additionally, we aim to examine the different types of users, including members and casual riders, as well as the usage of different types of bicycles, such as classic and electronic. Through our analysis, we hope to provide valuable insights to the Bikesharing service provider, which can inform future business decisions and service improvements.

Data¶

This project investigates the trip data from Citi Bike in New York City from March 2022 to Febuary 2023. There are 31,941,199 trips in total. Each entry has the start/end time and station, whether the user chose an electric bike or a a classic bike, whether the user was a member or a casual rider. We extract the date and weekday information from the start time. To enrich our dataset, we merged weather dataset (temperature, windspeed, rainy or snowy) on the date. Since we don't have detailed information about the riders, we merged demographics from each community district (median household income, the proportion of people having car-free commute, the average time people spend on commute, etc.) based on the start station location to our dataset in hope that these demographics can provide at least some information about the riders.

Problem Summary¶

  1. Predict daily bike demand based on weekday, weather information
  2. Classify bike type based on trip details, weather information, and demographical features
  3. Classify user type based on trip details, and demographical features

Conclusion and Discussion¶

To predict daily bike demand, we have trained linear, ridge and lasso regression. We utilized GridSearchCV to tune ridge and lasso. The best model is lasso with an alpha of 268.67. The R squared of the test set is 0.43, which means our model explained 43% of the variance in the target variable, which is not very good. But considering that we only have limited features, it's acceptable. In terms of coefficients, we can see that the predominant feature is 'feelslike', which is what we expected.

For the second research question to classify bicycle type, we use three methods, including Logistics Regression, KNN, and Random Forest.

Conclusion and Discussion¶

To predict bicycle type, we have trained three models, including KNN, Logistics Regression, and Random Forest Classifier. Among three models, we utilized GridSearchCV to tune each model, and derive three optimal models. Specifically, the best logistics regression has a f1 score of 0.57, the best KNN has a f1 score of 0.54, and the best random forest has a f1 score of 0.59. This is based on cross validation performance, which will be used as a measurement to select the model. We therefore select Random Forest with 130 n_estimators, 10 max_depth, and 2 min_samples_split as the final model. We further use this model to fit our test set, which has an overall accuracy rate of 0.58. The overall performance is considerably fair. However, it should be noted that the performance is not well-balanced across two classes. Specifically, the Electronic class has a precision score 0.30, and the Classic class has a precision score of 0.81. The gap between two classes is about 0.5, which is quite alerting. This is mostly likely due to the fact that we simply have less data with "electronic" labels. Even if we use upsample to achieve a classbalance when training the model, there is still lack of information to help us better predict eletronic bike.

(Additional) Problem 3: Membership¶

For the third question to predict user type, we choose to use Gradient Boosting Classifier, XGBoosting, Stochastic Gradient Descent Classifier. We choose three methods because they are all powerful machine learning algorithms that can handle complex datasets and have been shown to perform well in various classification tasks.

  1. Gradient Boosting Classifier is a boosting algorithm that combines multiple weak learners to form a strong learner, which can achieve high accuracy on complex datasets.

  2. XGBoosting is an optimized version of Gradient Boosting, which uses a more advanced regularization technique and parallel processing to speed up the training process and improve the model performance.

  3. Stochastic Gradient Descent Classifier is a linear classifier that can handle large datasets and converge quickly, which makes it suitable for real-time applications.

Considering that our previous classification model often suffer computational cost and underperform when coming to large-scale data, by using these three algorithms, we can explore different modeling techniques and choose the best-performing model to answer our research question.

Conclusion and Discussion¶

The best model among the three additional models is GradientBoostingClassifier, which has a CV f1 score of 0.644 and an accuracy of 0.64 in the test set. But overall the performance of the three models is about the same. Our model can classify the member class pretty well with an f1 score of 0.74. Our model struggled to predict the casual users with a precision of only 0.32. This is probably because there is a serious class imbalance between members and casual users, about 4:1. Plus, we don't have access to personal information about the users.

Overall Conclusions and Discussions¶

For bike demand prediction, we have a R squared of 0.43 given by lasso regression. For the classification tasks, we have an f1 score of 0.59 in terms of bike type given by Random Forest Classifier, and 0.64 in terms of user type given by XGBoosting Classifier. The overall performance is not very ideal but considering that we lack important relevant information (for example, station information like how many ebikes/classic bikes are available, user information like age), the performance is acceptable.

Future Work¶

Our future work will mainly focus on two aspects regarding (1) using Google Colab to run large scale dataset, (2) integrating additional real-time data provided by New York Citi Bike Live Station Feed API, (3) developing unsupervised model for user type prediction.

  1. Use Google Colab To Analyze Large-scale Dataset: our original data is considered to be large-scale, with 1,600,000 data samples. We have experienced several challenges when running model on our own computers possibly due to hardware and application memory limitations. To solve this issue, we proceeded our project by selecting a small fraction, about 2.5% of samples to answer our three proposed questions. For classification models, due to higher computational cost, we further reduced the sample size with a fraction of 0.05. While we believe that the sample size is solid for most model training, tuning, and validation, we hope that we could benefit the large scale data in the future by using Google Colab. Since Google Colab provides a free cloud computing environment, it will be particularly useful for us who don't have access to powerful hardware to work with large-scale dataset.

  2. Integrate Real-time API To Improve Classification Model Accuracy: Our current analysis does not include real-time data which provides more information on both users and vehicles, such as user pricing plan and the rated power of the motor for different vehicle types. The real-time data can be accessed from General Bikeshare Feed Specification (GBFS), see further reference here: https://github.com/MobilityData/gbfs/blob/master/gbfs.md#term-definitions. For future improvement, we consider to integrate real-time data into our analysis, as it may provides more understanding for user behaviours, customer profiles, and bikesharing usage trend. Consequently, we are likely to improve accuracy rate of our existing classification model to predict user type and vehicle type.

  3. Utilize Unsupervised Models such as K-means to Predict User Type: The classification accuracy rate to predict user type have futher potential for improvement, and we think unsupervised model such as K-means clustering can serve as a good attempt. Our current challenge is that we do not enough information about the users such as demographical and socioeconomic features, and hence, the omitted variables prevent us to classifying the user type more accurately. With K-means clustering, we might better understand user behaviours and categorize properly.
